Randall Robinson, a prominent figure in the fight for justice and human rights, passed away. His childhood experiences with poverty and segregation shaped his determination to make a difference in the lives of others. From his legal aid work in Boston to his international advocacy, Randall worked tirelessly to improve the lives of millions and advance the cause of justice. As the leader of TransAfrica, he built connections and secured rights for the African Diaspora. He even risked his own health to protect Haitians fleeing violence. His work with the Free South Africa Movement inspired a global outcry and helped end generations of oppression. Randall's writings reflected his experiences and his disappointment with the slow pace of progress. Let us honor his memory by continuing to fight for a better America and never forgetting the power of individuals to change the world.